          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Khartoum reclaimed</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/sudan-military-chief-gen-burhan-arrives-republican-palace-recaptured-khartoum.png" alt="Sudan's military chief Gen. Abdel-Fattah Burhan center, is greeted by troops as he arrives at the Republican Palace, recently recaptured from the Rapid Support Forces paramilitary group, in Khartoum, Sudan" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Sudan's military chief Gen. Abdel-Fattah Burhan center, is greeted by troops as he arrives at the Republican Palace, recently recaptured from the Rapid Support Forces paramilitary group, in Khartoum, Sudan. Credits: AP Photo</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The two-year civil war has hit a turning point. Sudan’s de facto leader, General Abdel Fattah al-Burhan, has declared that <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-03-2025-h1-1-khartoum-is-free" target="_blank">Khartoum is free</a>. Sudanese government forces recaptured the capital from the Rapid Support Forces (RSF). After retaking key RSF bases, Burhan celebrated the victory at the presidential palace and Khartoum International Airport.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          While government troops have advanced in Khartoum and central Sudan, the war still rages with no end in sight. The RSF maintains control over substantial areas in western Sudan, particularly Darfur, with increasing fears of a potential partition. The conflict began in 2023 when the RSF seized Khartoum. Despite initial cooperation between the army and RSF to oust Omar al-Bashir in 2019, tensions led to the 2021 coup and the subsequent civil war.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The humanitarian losses are severe. Many Sudanese have been displaced, and the death toll is said to be between 60,000 and 150,000. There have also been mass atrocities committed by both the RSD and the Sudanese government forces. The UN has labeled Sudan’s situation the world's worst humanitarian crisis.</p>
        </mj-text>
