          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Trump backs McGregor</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Trump’s invitation to Conor McGregor for St. Patrick’s Day has caused noise and raised questions on the Trumpification of Ireland.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">UFC star Conor McGregor has stirred up political tensions in Ireland after being <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-03-2025-h3-3-invited-to-white-house" target="_blank">invited to the White House</a> on St. Patrick's Day by President Trump. McGregor was found liable for rape in a Dublin hotel and is facing a civil trial for alleged sexual assault in Florida. Many in Ireland found him an inappropriate guest to invite for such an occasion.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">McGregor's visit is part of Trump’s broader efforts to court Europe's far-right movements, aligning with figures like Hungary's Viktor Orbán and Italy's Giorgia Meloni. McGregor's potential presidential candidacy in Ireland reflects growing hard-right sentiments. However, constitutional barriers and a lack of support from the required 20 Irish parliament members make his presidential run unlikely.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The backlash from the middle class is intense, especially as the country faces issues like homelessness and immigration. McGregor's association with Trump has raised concerns about far-right politics and their impact on Irish society.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
