          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇰🇵 North Korea sent 3,000 more troops to Russia this year</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">North Korea has sent <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-03-2025-br2-5-3000-more-soldiers-to-russia" target="_blank">3,000 more soldiers to Russia</a>, bringing the total to 11,000. Four thousand have already been killed or injured in combat, per South Korea’s military. Pyongyang has also supplied missiles, artillery, and rocket launchers to Moscow. North Korean troops were conscripted to Kursk to repel Ukraine’s incursion since at least November. But they withdrew from the front lines earlier this year due to mass casualties.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Moscow agreed to a partial truce in the Black Sea but demanded that sanctions be lifted. Kim Jong Un plans to visit Russia soon. The US warns that Russia will provide Pyongyang with advanced military technology in exchange for its support. Despite the ongoing negotiations and partial ceasefire, Russian drone strikes continue to strike Ukraine.</p>
        </mj-text>
